\section{Implemented methods}{


\strong{1. WHO} \code{Tmin < P10(Tmin)} for >= N consecutive days (default N=3).
Threshold smoothed over a 15-day rolling window by calendar day-of-year.
Reference: WMO & WHO (2015).

\strong{2. WMO} \verb{Tmin < P10(Tmin) AND Tmax < P10(Tmax)} for >= N days (default
N=5). Double threshold ensures both daytime and nighttime extremes are
captured. Reference: Perkins & Alexander (2013).

\strong{3. INMET} \verb{Tmin < mean(Tmin_hist) - 5 degC} for >= N days (default N=5).
Climatological mean from the baseline period. Designed for Brazilian context.

\strong{4. ECF} Excess Cold Factor: \verb{ECF = ECI_sig x max(1, ECI_acc)} where
\code{ECI_sig = P5(Tmean) - T3} and \code{ECI_acc = T30 - T3}. Intensity classified
by ECF85 (85th percentile of positive ECF values). Adaptation of Nairn &
Fawcett (2015) for cold extremes. Positive \code{ECI_acc} means the preceding
month was warmer than the recent 3-day mean (body acclimatised to heat,
amplifying cold stress).

\strong{5. UTCI} \code{UTCImin < P10(UTCImin)} for >= N days (default N=3). Requires
\code{utci_c} column from \code{sus_climate_compute_indicators()}.

\strong{6. WBGT} \code{WBGTmin < P10(WBGTmin)} for >= N days (default N=3). Requires
\code{wbgt_c} column from \code{sus_climate_compute_indicators()}.

\strong{7. HI} \code{HImin < P10(HImin)} for >= N days (default N=3). Requires \code{hi_c}
column from \code{sus_climate_compute_indicators()}.
